✦
On Pastoral Theology and the Accusation of Overthinking
This book is pastoral theology of desire.
The distinction from philosophy is precise. Philosophy describes and argues.
Pastoral theology educates practitioners in how to live. How to inhabit the framework fully rather than partially. How to recognize the aspirational self clearly
enough to pursue it honestly. How to sustain the charge over years rather than
scenes. How to be a Priest who does not erode. How to be an initiate who does
not perform surrender while withholding it.
The Prolegomena is the foundation that makes the pastoral purpose possible.
You cannot teach people to live a framework they do not understand. Book One
gives the understanding. Books Two through Five teach the living.
This book is specifically addressed to practitioners of Master/initiate dynamics.
To the ones who own and the ones who yield.
To the ones who have been trying to live this framework
with inadequate language for what it is.
And therefore it must answer the central accusation leveled at nearly all of
them.
67

The Central Thesis
On the Accusation of Overthinking
You have been told: you are overthinking what can just be lived.
This accusation arrives from people who mean well. Who live their own desire in the simplified register the culture makes available — visual attraction, physical consummation, the feeling a framework is unnecessary. the feeling itself is sufficient. For them, the feeling is sufficient. Their aspirational self does not require
the framework to be conscious and named. They can simply live.
You cannot.
Not because you are more complicated than other people— though you may
be. Because your specific aspirational self is organized around the hierarchical
framework in a way that makes the framework’s absence not a simplification but
a deprivation. You have tried living without conscious naming of the dynamic.
What you found was not simplicity. What you found was a chronic, specific,
nameless dissatisfaction — the experience of someone who is hungry for a particular food and is being told that hunger itself is the problem.
You are not overthinking.
You are the person for whom the unspoken framework
produces a specific and permanent incompleteness.
This book speaks to that incompleteness.
Not to resolve it through further simplification.
To give it language adequate to what it is.
The people who can just live it are not wrong.
They do not need this book.
You do.
The volumes that follow are not philosophy. They are, in the terms established by van Gennep and Turner, liminal texts: texts that exist in the threshold
space between the ordinary world and the sacred one45 They should be read not as
description but as invitation — and more than invitation: as instruction. As the
education in conscious inhabitation the culture has consistently failed to provide.
68

VII. How To Read What Follows
Rudolf Otto’s concept of the numinous — the mysterium tremendum et
fascinans46 — is the appropriate register for what follows. Not because the material is mystical in the soft sense. Because it is genuinely other — genuinely outside
the range the culture has designated as ordinary — and it requires a register adequate to that otherness.
The philosophy established in this Prolegomena has prepared the ground.
The theology that follows does not argue.
It educates.
It enacts.
The philosophy has drawn the map.
What follows is not argument but inhabitation.
The language shifts. The object shifts —
from analysis of desire
to the theology of those who live it.
If you have crossed this far,
the register change will not surprise you.
Every structure, named completely enough, becomes a god.
Voice of Decho
✦
You believe you discovered hierarchy.
You did not.
It existed before you spoke.
Before you were born.
69

