III.
The Penis As Sacred Object
✦
On the Cult’s Central Object of Devotion
The great phallic cults knew something
the modern world has tried to forget.
The Hermae that stood at every crossroads in Athens —
stone columns topped with the head of Hermes
and below, erect and unashamed, the phallus.
Not as obscenity.
As protection. As boundary. As the god made present.
The erect penis at the threshold
told the world: here is a claim.
Here is a boundary held by force.
Here is the god of this space.
Priapus in the Roman garden —
the grotesque, oversized, eternally erect deity
who guarded the orchard against thieves.
His weapon was the phallus itself.
His deterrent was not violence but exposure —
the god who said: I see you.
I am here.
80

III. The Penis As Sacred Object
Nothing passes without my acknowledgment.
The Shiva lingam, oldest sacred object of continuous worship —
the abstract column of generative force
still bathed in milk and flowers in ten thousand temples.
Not the man’s organ but the principle it represents:
the creative force that cannot be contained,
that erupts through form,
that is simultaneously destroyer and generator,
that demands total devotion
precisely. it answers to nothing.
These cults understood what the dark cult of Decho also knows:
The penis is not primarily a sexual organ.
It is a theological statement.
It is the body’s most naked claim to presence,
to power, to the right to occupy space,
to the force that insists on itself
regardless of permission.
The one who has made peace with his penis —
who carries it not with shame or performance
but with the specific gravity
of someone who understands what he is carrying —
