V. The Crowning — The Mutual Dependency
V.
The Crowning - The Mutual Dependency
✦
And here is the argument that contains all the others.
The Master needs the initiate. More than he will ever admit in public.
Completely.
Without remainder.
An Alpha without an initiate is a man with an orientation. Real, genuine,
carried honestly. But not yet a Master. A Master is not constituted by his orientation alone — he is constituted by the initiate’s choosing. The initiate crowns the
Alpha. Not metaphorically. Structurally. The crown is given, not taken. And it
can only be given freely, by the one who chooses to give it.
This is why everything in this chapter matters.
The sustainability. The heavy lifting. The safety.
The distinction between pain and harm.
These are not moral prescriptions from outside the dynamic.
They are structural requirements derived from inside it.
The Master who violates them is not being immoral.
He is dismantling the only architecture
in which he can be himself.
The moment the initiate’s willing participation is withdrawn— because trust
was broken, because harm replaced pain, for the dynamic became overbearing,.
the Master stopped maintaining what the initiate submitted into — the Master ceases to be a Master. He remains a person. Possibly a strong man, a dominant man, a man with a specific gravitational field. But without the initiate who
chooses him, he is an Alpha without a crown. A title with no one to confer it. An
orientation with no circuit to complete it.
It is worth sitting with the specific beauty of this.
Two identities, so individually defined,
221

