III.
What Starves the Charge
✦
Assumption
Covered above. The single most effective way to starve the charge. Treat the
dynamic as a fixed object and the dynamic will demonstrate, with complete patience, that it is not.
Performance Without Presence
The protocol executed correctly but without the god behind it. The ritual
performed to completion. The scene constructed with technical precision. And
both parties knowing, quietly, the god is not in the room.
Performance without presence produces a specific and unmistakable quality
of hollow. The body knows. The body always knows. The charge is not there
for the god is not there. the man is not there — he is executing a role rather than
inhabiting a reality.
The specific tragedy of performance without presence: both parties often collude in it. Because the alternative — naming the absence, sitting with the hollow,
having the honest conversation about why the god is not in the room today —
requires a courage the performance, paradoxically, makes easier to avoid. The
performance gives both parties something to do. The honest absence gives them
only each other. the truth.
When the performance feels hollow —
stop the performance.
Sit in the absence.
Name it.
228

III. What Starves the Charge
The god returns through honesty,
not through technique.
Suppressing the God in Civilian Contexts
The specific failure of the one who has learned, to function in ordinary life,
to suppress the god so thoroughly that he loses access to him.
The civilian world requires management. It requires the suppression of the
primal, the modulation of the intense, the reduction of the charge to a level the
social context can accommodate. This is not wrong — it is necessary. The Priest
of Dechowho brings the full charge of the god into eprofessional meeting, efamily
dinner, ecasual social interaction, has confused presence with imposition.
But the one who manages the god so thoroughly, for so long, in so many
contexts, that he loses the ability to access him in the contexts where access is appropriate — this man has solved the wrong problem.
The solution is not suppression.
The solution is calibration.
The god at full current in the right contexts.
The god contained but present in the ordinary ones.
Never suppressed.
Never absent.
Always available.
Calibrated to the room.
229

