The Semiotics of Public Inhabitation
✦
The body of the Priest of Decho, moving through public space, is a text. It speaks
— in the specific language of body, presence. deliberate preparation — to those
who have the language to read it.
The shaved body. The specific posture of a person who takes up exactly the
space he occupies, no more and no less. The quality of eye contact that is complete
without being aggressive — the gaze that says I see what I see and am not afraid
of what I find, offered briefly to anyone who meets it, without demand, without
performance. The clothing that is not armor or costume but simply the careful
presentation of a body that has been tended with purpose.
This text is legible at two levels simultaneously. To the uninitiated: a man
with good posture and a certain quality of presence. Something that makes them
slightly more comfortable or slightly more uncomfortable, depending on their
own orientation, without their being able to name why. To the initiated — to the
person who carries the complementary framework or who shares the orientation
— the text is entirely legible. This man is a Priest. He carries the god. He has done
the interior work. The framework is present in him.
The signal is public.
The signal is coded.
It is legible to those with the language
and background noise to those without it.
This is the cult’s specific elegance.
It does not hide. It does not perform.
It simply inhabits — and lets those who can read it, read it.
