have chosen it. The workplace is not that.
The Street, the Transit, the Unremarkable Passage
The city is the Priest’s natural element.
Berlin at night. The specific quality of a city that has been broken and rebuilt
and broken again and carries all of its history in its geography. The canal. The
unremarkable bridge. The man crossing it alone at midnight, carrying the god,
reading the city through the lens that makes it alive.
The city is alive to the practitioner in a way it is not alive to the one who
moves through it in managed suppression. Each face contains a story he can read.
Each building carries the accumulated weight of the people who have inhabited
it. Each street has a hierarchy — of presence, of danger, of specific beauty that
is only visible to the eye that is genuinely open. The Priest moves through this
city as a native moves through their language: fluently, without effort, reading
the subtext that is invisible to the tourist.
On the street, the god is simply present.
Not directed. Not performing. Present.
The field operates as fields operate:
