III. The Initiate Vets the Master — The Mutual Examination
III.
The Initiate Vets the Master - The Mutual Examination
✦
The vetting is not one-directional.
The initiate vets the Master.
This is not a courtesy.
It is a structural necessity.
The initiate who yields completely to a Master they have not examined is not
practicing wisdom — they are practicing hope. And hope, in this context, is a
dangerous foundation. The complete surrender the dynamic requires can only
be offered safely to a person who has demonstrated they are capable of receiving
it. The initiate who does not vet is setting up the structure for harm.
The vetting from the initiate to the Master reveals a great deal.
How does this person respond to questions about their relational history?
Do they have a history of sustained commitment, or a series of exits? Do they
carry their previous relationships with honesty, or with contempt — blaming,
diminishing, erasing? The person who speaks about former partners only as failures, only as people who didn’t understand, only as the reasons the relationship
was unworkable — is the person who has not examined themselves. The Master
who has not examined himself cannot examine his initiate.
How does this person respond when the interview does not go in their preferred direction? The Master who becomes cold when questioned, who withdraws or pressures when his authority is tested in conversation before it has been
consented to — is showing exactly how he will behave. the dynamic is under
stress. The real Master can be questioned. He can be examined. He remains himself in the examination. His authority does not require the other person’s advance
submission to remain intact.
How does this person speak about the dynamic itself? With gravity and care,
or with entitlement? With the understanding that they are describing something
that requires the other person’s full consent and full self-knowledge, or with the
