IV. The Master Is Not Santa Claus — On the Wish List as Diagnostic
IV.
The Master Is Not Santa Claus - On the Wish List as Diagnostic
✦
The vetting process reveals a specific misunderstanding with such consistency that
it deserves its own examination.
Some practitioners arrive at the dynamic as if it were a procurement problem. A catalog of requirements — specific acts, specific protocols, specific demonstrations of Master-status — against which the person across from them will be
assessed for adequacy. The Master who does not produce the required items is
found wanting. The arrangement is declared non-viable. The search continues.
This is worth examining carefully,. it is not simply frustrating.
It is diagnostic.
The practitioner who approaches the Master with a checklist has not yet encountered the frequency. They know the vocabulary of the dynamic — the terminology, the structure, the formal requirements. What they are missing is the
experience of the genuine thing, which cannot be requested in advance. Not a
service. a recognition. And recognition cannot be itemized.
The checklist is the instrument of the person working from description rather
than experience. They have read about the frequency without yet having been in
its range. This is not a failure. It is a stage.
The Master found wanting by the checklist
was not found wanting.
He was found.
When the genuine thing arrives, the checklist becomes irrelevant.
That is how the practitioner knows it was genuine.
247

Chapter Four: DATING AND VETTING
V.
On Structure - Order as the Neighbor of God
✦
The Swedish director Ingmar Bergman said that order is the neighbor of God.
He was not speaking about theology in the conventional sense — he was
speaking about what he knew from making films. That without rigorous structure, no freedom. That the improvisation that appears spontaneous is possible
only. the foundation beneath it was built with care. That art without order is not
liberation — it is noise.
This book exists partly. of that conviction.
The dynamic this theology describes can be lived intuitively by some people—
carried in the body, practiced without language, maintained without the systematic examination these pages represent. Some people find the thing and inhabit it
without needing to name it. This is real. This is possible.
But for most practitioners, in a culture that has provided no adequate language for what they are — that has instead provided shame, misunderstanding,
the wish-list model, the performance model, the Santa Claus model — the intuitive inhabitation is not available. The signal is buried under the accumulated
instructions of a culture that could not read it.
Structure is the instrument of excavation.
The structure this book provides — the philosophical foundation, the theology, the liturgy, the daily practice, the protocols, the vetting process, the red flags,
the distinction between pain and harm — is not a cage. It is scaffolding. It exists
to make the inhabitation possible for the person who could not find it without
language. Once the thing is found, the scaffolding can be removed or forgotten.
But finding it required the structure.
Without structure, no order.
Without order, no dynamic.
Without the dynamic, the orientation exists
only as chronic, nameless, unmet longing.
248

