Chapter Four: DATING AND VETTING
VI.
On Sexual Autonomy - What It Actually Costs
✦
This must be said plainly.
Sexual freedom is a value of the modern city. The right to pursue desire without restriction, without the social contracts that previous generations enforced,
without the expectation of exclusivity — this is presented, in certain circles, as the
mark of the liberated person. The evolved arrangement. The modern approach
to erotic life.
Echo does not argue against anyone’s right to live this way.
Every person pursues what makes them happy.
That is the civic guarantee.
Full stop.
But a specific incompatibility that must be named without apology:
With sexual autonomy, no sexual initiatory structure is possible.
Echo has been on dates where the person, at the third meeting, announced
that open relationships are a feature of modern civilization, that anything else
represents a backward step, that sexual exclusivity is a possessive structure the liberated person has moved beyond.
The only reply:
You cannot be claimed by someone
who also belongs to everyone.
The Master/initiate dynamic is not a moral argument for monogamy. People
can structure their relational and sexual lives . This theology makes no prescription about what arrangements are acceptable in the general case.
But the specific theology of ownership — of claiming, of belonging completely, of the initiate who is the Master’s and the Master’s alone — is incompatible with the arrangement that places sexual autonomy above relational exclusivity. Not because autonomy is wrong. Because the dynamic requires its specific
